{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17643912","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17643912"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:59:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:59:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18024"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18024","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18024"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.17,0.78,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10738"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78255"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10738","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10738"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18024"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63667"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1167"},{"type":"tags","id":"1217"},{"type":"tags","id":"2597"},{"type":"tags","id":"3981"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8133"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25003"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25005"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26846"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78255","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78255"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe various parts of the body can be best visualised by certain imaging modalities. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is considered the gold standard for imaging the spinal cord?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["X-ray","CT","MRI","Ultrasound","PET"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMRI\u003C/strong\u003E is considered the gold standard for imaging the spinal cord due to its excellent soft tissue contrast, which allows for detailed visualisation of the spinal cord, nerve roots, and surrounding structures. It is particularly useful in assessing conditions such as spinal cord compression, tumours, and demyelinating diseases. Here is an example, showing spinal cord stenosis (Image).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EX-ray\u003C/strong\u003E is limited in its ability to visualise soft tissues and is primarily used for assessing bony structures. It is not suitable for detailed evaluation of the spinal cord.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT\u003C/strong\u003E provides better detail of bony structures compared to X-ray but is less effective than MRI in visualising soft tissues like the spinal cord. It may be used in cases where MRI is contraindicated or unavailable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUltrasound\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically used for imaging the spinal cord in adults due to its limited penetration and resolution in this context. It is more commonly used in neonates where the spinal canal is more accessible.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPET\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily used for metabolic imaging and is not suitable for detailed anatomical imaging of the spinal cord. It is used in oncology to assess metabolic activity of tumours.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Magnetic Resonance Imaging (MRI) is the gold standard for imaging the spinal cord due to its superior soft tissue contrast and ability to visualize the spinal cord, nerve roots, and surrounding structures.","MRI is non-invasive and does not involve ionizing radiation, making it a safer option for repeated imaging.","Other imaging modalities like CT and X-ray are less effective in visualizing soft tissue structures such as the spinal cord."],"references":["Fehrenbach, M. J., \u0026 Herring, S. W. (2015). Illustrated Anatomy of the Head and Neck-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","McCausland C, Sawyer E, Eovaldi BJ, et al. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder Muscles. [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK534836/","Cramer, G. D., \u0026 Darby, S. A. (2013). Clinical anatomy of the spine, spinal cord, and ANS","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","Bozzo, A., Marcoux, J., Radhakrishna, M., Pelletier, J., \u0026 Goulet, B. (2011). The role of magnetic resonance imaging in the management of acute spinal cord injury. Journal of neurotrauma, 28(8), 1401\u20131411. https://doi.org/10.1089/neu.2009.1236","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63667"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18024"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21448"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21448","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21448"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/Tz8YkSXYnw2Ey2MFvGCdU4zgfGidgf.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/Tz8YkSXYnw2Ey2MFvGCdU4zgfGidgf.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":293,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63667","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63667"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-10T10:21:13+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-10T10:21:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10738"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78255"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"